In [[statistics]], the '''Freedman&ndash;Diaconis rule''' can be used to select the width of the bins to be used in a [[histogram]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Freedman|first=David|last2=Diaconis|first2=Persi|date=December 1981|year=|title=On the histogram as a density estimator: ''L''<sub>2</sub> theory|url=http://www.springerlink.com/content/mp364022824748n3/fulltext.pdf|format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]|journal=Probability Theory and Related Fields|location=Heidelberg|publisher=Springer Berlin|volume=57|issue=4|pages=453–476|doi=10.1007/BF01025868|issn=0178-8051|via=|authorlink=David Freedman (statistician)|authorlink2=Persi Diaconis|accessdate=2009-01-06}}</ref> It is named after [[David A. Freedman]] and [[Persi Diaconis]].
For a set of empirical measurements sampled from some [[probability distribution]], the Freedman-Diaconis rule is designed to minimize the difference between the [[integral|area under the empirical probability distribution]] and the area under the theoretical probability distribution.{{Clarify|reason=What is the empirical probability distribution? Why would minimizing this difference be a good thing?|date=June 2017}}
The general equation for the rule is:
:<math>\text{Bin width}=2\, { \text{IQR}(x) \over{ \sqrt[3]{n} }}</math>
where <math>\operatorname{IQR}(x) </math> is the [[interquartile range]] of the data and <math> n </math> is the number of observations in the sample <math> x. </math>
==Other approaches== Another approach is to use [[Histogram#Number_of_bins_and_width|''Sturges' rule'']]: use a bin so large that there are about <math>\scriptstyle 1+\log_2n</math> non-empty bins (Scott, 2009).<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Scott | first1 = D.W. | year = 2009 | title = Sturges' rule | url = | journal = WIREs Computational Statistics | volume = 1 | issue = | pages = 303–306 | doi=10.1002/wics.35}}</ref> This works well for ''n'' under 200, but was found to be inaccurate for large&nbsp;''n''.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hyndman | first1 = R.J. | year = 1995 | title = The problem with Sturges’ rule for constructing histograms | url = http://robjhyndman.com/papers/sturges.pdf | journal = | volume = | issue = | pages = | doi= }}</ref> For a discussion and an alternative approach, see Birgé and Rozenholc.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Birgé | first1 = L. | last2 = Rozenholc | first2 = Y. | year = 2006 | title = How many bins should be put in a regular histogram | url = http://www.numdam.org/item?id=PS_2006__10__24_0 | journal = ESAIM: Probability and Statistics | volume = 10 | issue = | pages = 24–45 | doi=10.1051/ps:2006001| citeseerx = 10.1.1.3.220 }}</ref>
