{{Infobox book| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Hegira | title_orig = | translator = | image = Hegira -- bookcover.jpg | caption = Cover of first edition (hardcover) | author = [[Greg Bear]] | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = [[Science fiction]] | publisher = Dell | release_date = 1979 | media_type = Print (hardback & paperback) | pages = 158 | isbn = 0-7592-0684-8 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= 78206984 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Hegira''''' is a 1979 [[science fiction]] novel by [[US|American]] writer [[Greg Bear]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hegira by Greg Bear|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1763383.Hegira|website=[[Goodreads]]|publisher=goodreads.com|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> It deals with themes including [[cyclic time]], [[artificial intelligence]], [[artificial life]], and artificial structures of planetary scale.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Langford|first1=Dave|title=Greg Bear Hegira|url=http://ansible.uk/writing/hegira.html|publisher=ansible.uk|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=HEGIRA: Bear, Greg|url=https://www.abebooks.com/servlet/BookDetailsPL?bi=14486506448&searchurl=tn%3Dhegira%26sortby%3D17%26an%3Dgreg%2Bbear%26sgnd%3Don|publisher=abebooks.com|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>
==Plot summary== In the novel, "young" humans (recreations of the medieval originals) are transported through the [[Big Collapse]], at the end of time, to seed the next cycle of the universe. They are transported to Hegira, an [[artificial world|artificial environment]] of the scale of the planet [[Jupiter]], which has habitats for several species on its surface. The habitats are protected and uncoupled from the universe's [[entropy]] by means of [[force shield|force fields]] projected by giant [[obelisk]]s. In the human realm, these are inscribed with the recorded history of humankind, sorted chronologically from the bottom up, including the science that went with it. People try to understand and copy what they can read on the obelisks, using balloons in some places to reach higher points on the obelisks.<!--"Each city they pass through shows a different facet of how a human community might develop given slight differing versions of the basic information provided by the obelisks"-->
A legend tells the protagonist that his beloved (frozen in [[stasis (fiction)|stasis]]) will awaken if he goes on quest to the rim walls of the habitat, and he does so. On the way, he lands on an island with a good view of an obelisk (at least {{convert|1000|mi|km|abbr=on}} high) which is just tumbling down in the distance. Its fall causes a [[tsunami]] and devastates a continent. After the devastation, the inscriptions at the top of the fallen obelisk about human history are revealed. The hero's quest to the rim succeeds. He makes contact with an artificial intelligence guardian of Hegira, who tells him the story and advises him to go and populate the new universe since he has become part of the last one.
